# This is a regression test for a bug in the capped multiplier model:
# computeCPUCapacityWithCap subtracts background CPU when
# deriving per-store capacity, which mistakenly broke the naive
# model's invariant:
#
#   sum(store loads) / sum(store capacities) = NodeCPURateUsage / NodeCPURateCapacity
#
# Setup: single node n1 with two stores.
# - s1: store CPU load = 0.1 cores, s2: store CPU load = 0.3 cores
# - Physical node CPU: load = 0.8 cores, capacity = 2 cores.
#   The gap (0.8 - 0.4 = 0.4 cores) is background CPU that the capped
#   model excluded from store capacities.
#
# With the capped model, n1's store values no longer recover the
# physical node utilization:
#
#   sum(store loads) / sum(store capacities) = 0.4/2 = 20%
#   NodeCPURateUsage / NodeCPURateCapacity   = 0.8/2 = 40%  (real)
#
# MakeStoreLoadMsg addresses this by passing physical node CPU values
# directly through StoreLoadMsg.NodeCPULoad/NodeCPUCapacity.
#
# Without the fix, NodeCPULoad would be derived from store sums:
#
#   nodes-cpu-load = 0.4 cores  (sum of stores, but real node CPU = 0.8 cores)
#   node utilization = 20%  (but real = 40%)
#
# With the fix:
#
#   nodes-cpu-load = 0.8 cores  (physical NodeCPURateUsage)
#   node utilization = 40%  (correct)
#
# All CPU values below are in ns/s (1 core = 1e9 ns/s).

# Register two stores on node 1.
set-store store-id=1 node-id=1
----

set-store store-id=2 node-id=1
----

# Store-level CPU loads: s1 = 0.1 cores, s2 = 0.3 cores (sum = 0.4 cores).
# Physical node CPU: load = 0.8 cores, capacity = 2 cores.
# mult = 0.8/0.4 = 2, background = 0.
# Per-store capacity = 2 / (2 * 2) = 0.5 cores.
#
# node-cpu-load = 0.8 cores (physical) differs from what summing store loads
# would give (0.4 cores).
make-store-load-msg store-id=1 node-id=1 num-stores=2 cpu-per-second=100000000 stores-cpu-rate=400000000 node-cpu-usage=800000000 node-cpu-capacity=2000000000
----
store-id=1 node-id=1 load=[100000000,0,0] capacity=[500000000,9223372036854775807,0] secondary-load=0 load-time=0s node-cpu-load=800000000 node-cpu-capacity=2000000000

make-store-load-msg store-id=2 node-id=1 num-stores=2 cpu-per-second=300000000 stores-cpu-rate=400000000 node-cpu-usage=800000000 node-cpu-capacity=2000000000
----
store-id=2 node-id=1 load=[300000000,0,0] capacity=[500000000,9223372036854775807,0] secondary-load=0 load-time=0s node-cpu-load=800000000 node-cpu-capacity=2000000000

# nodes-cpu-load = 0.8 cores (physical node value from MakeStoreLoadMsg),
# not 0.4 cores (what store-level summing would give). Node utilization
# is 40% (0.8/2), not 20% (0.4/2).
load-summary
----
cluster means: (stores-load [cpu:200ms/s, write-bandwidth:0 B/s, byte-size:0 B]) (stores-capacity [cpu:500ms/s, write-bandwidth:unknown/s, byte-size:0 B])
(nodes-cpu-load 800000000) (nodes-cpu-capacity 2000000000)
evaluating store s1 for shedding: load summary (store=loadNormal worst=WriteBandwidth cpu=loadLow writes=loadNormal bytes=loadNormal node=loadNormal frac_pending=0.00,0.00(true))evaluating store s2 for shedding: load summary (store=overloadSlow worst=CPURate cpu=overloadSlow writes=loadNormal bytes=loadNormal node=loadNormal frac_pending=0.00,0.00(true))

# Background CPU decreased: physical node CPU drops from 0.8 to 0.4 cores.
# Only s1 sends a new message; s2's store load is unchanged.
# mult = 0.4/0.4 = 1, background = 0.
# Per-store capacity = 2 / (1 * 2) = 1 core.
#
# Without the fix, this would have no effect on nodes-cpu-load
# because store loads are unchanged (sum stays 0.4 cores).
make-store-load-msg store-id=1 node-id=1 num-stores=2 cpu-per-second=100000000 stores-cpu-rate=400000000 node-cpu-usage=400000000 node-cpu-capacity=2000000000
----
store-id=1 node-id=1 load=[100000000,0,0] capacity=[1000000000,9223372036854775807,0] secondary-load=0 load-time=0s node-cpu-load=400000000 node-cpu-capacity=2000000000

# The StoreLoadMsg correctly carries node-cpu-load = 0.4 cores, but the
# load-summary shows the cached cluster means (0.8 cores) from the previous
# cycle. Means are recomputed at the start of each rebalance cycle, not on
# every load-summary call. The node's internal adjustedCPU was updated;
# the next rebalance-stores call would see the new value.
